{
  "updated_summary": "In a dimly lit, opulent Bedroom, a Young Woman in a light purple dress attempts to soothe a distressed Young Man, Colin, who lies thrashing in an ornate four-poster bed, pale and contorted. She reassures him about nonexistent lumps, attributing his perceived "backbone lumps" to his thinness and sharing her own past experience of being thinner. When Colin expresses fear about living to grow up, she encourages him, suggesting he'll live to be a hundred if he calms down and gets fresh air. He then asks about her day, specifically the garden, and she enthusiastically describes its rapid growth, mentioning that Dickon would be happy to push his wheelchair there, revealing his reliance on one. Colin resigns himself, stating Dr. Craven and Mrs. Medlock won't allow him outside, a statement the Young Woman finds confusing, believing he has authority. After a defiant laugh, Colin commands, \"We're going out and we want to be left alone, Medlock.\" The camera pans across heavy drapes and flickering candlelight, heightening the tension. The scene shifts to an exterior of the House, where an Elderly Man in a dark coat sits sternly in an armchair, while a tall, authoritative Woman in Black Dress points accusingly, admonishing him as \"Master Colin!\" and reminding him he is a \"very sick boy.\" The Elderly Man, holding a Book with a tense expression, is met by Colin's anguished retort, \"That is precisely what I must forget.\" The Young Woman remains by his side, worried, amidst the dim candlelight. The final exterior shot shows the Woman in Black Dress pointing at the Elderly Man, who looks up with fear and defiance, with the stone house in the background under a clear sky."
}
